          "text": "Here's what the codebase supports:\n\n**Streamable HTTP: Yes**\n\nThe MCP client in `crates/librefang-runtime/src/mcp.rs` supports the **Streamable HTTP transport** (MCP 2025-03-26 spec). It's implemented via the `rmcp` SDK's `StreamableHttpClientTransport`, which handles:\n- `Accept: application/json, text/event-stream` content negotiation\n- `Mcp-Session-Id` session tracking\n- SSE stream parsing and fallback\n\nYou configure it with the `Http` transport variant:\n```toml\n[mcp_servers.example]\ntransport = { type = \"http\", url = \"https://example.com/mcp\" }\nheaders = [\"Authorization: Bearer <token>\"]\n```\n\n**OAuth for MCP: No**\n\nThere is **no built-in OAuth flow for MCP connections**. The MCP transport accepts static `headers` (line 48) for auth — you'd manually set an `Authorization: Bearer <token>` header. There's no automatic token acquisition, refresh, or PKCE flow tied to MCP server connections.\n\nThe codebase *does* have OAuth2 PKCE support (`crates/librefang-extensions/src/oauth.rs`) for **extensions/channels** (Google, GitHub, Microsoft, Slack), but this is separate infrastructure not wired into the MCP client. There's also `copilot_oauth.rs` and `chatgpt_oauth.rs` for specific provider auth flows, but again these are not MCP-related.\n\n**Summary**: Streamable HTTP transport works. If you need OAuth-authenticated MCP servers, you'd currently need to obtain tokens externally and pass them via the `headers` config field.",
