          "text": "Here's how to get a Notion OAuth token for use with their MCP server:\n\n## Step 1: Create a Notion Integration\n\n1. Go to **https://www.notion.so/profile/integrations**\n2. Click **\"New integration\"**\n3. Fill in:\n   - **Name**: whatever you want (e.g. \"LibreFang MCP\")\n   - **Associated workspace**: select your workspace\n4. Under **Type**, select **\"Public\"** (required for OAuth)\n5. Under **Capabilities**, enable what you need (read content, read comments, etc.)\n6. Set the **Redirect URI** to `http://localhost:3333/callback` (or any local URL you can listen on)\n7. Click **Submit**\n8. Note the **Client ID** and **Client Secret** from the integration page\n\n## Step 2: Build the Authorization URL\n\nOpen this URL in your browser (replace `YOUR_CLIENT_ID`):\n\n```\nhttps://api.notion.com/v1/oauth/authorize?client_id=YOUR_CLIENT_ID&response_type=code&owner=user&redirect_uri=http%3A%2F%2Flocalhost%3A3333%2Fcallback\n```\n\n## Step 3: Listen for the Callback\n\nBefore opening that URL, start a temporary listener to capture the auth code:\n\n```bash\n# Quick one-shot server using Python\npython3 -c \"\nfrom http.server import HTTPServer, BaseHTTPRequestHandler\nfrom urllib.parse import urlparse, parse_qs\n\nclass Handler(BaseHTTPRequestHandler):\n    def do_GET(self):\n        query = parse_qs(urlparse(self.path).query)\n        code = query.get('code', [''])[0]\n        self.send_response(200)\n        self.end_headers()\n        self.wfile.write(f'Got code: {code}\\nYou can close this tab.'.encode())\n        print(f'\\n==> Authorization code: {code}\\n')\n\nHTTPServer(('localhost', 3333), Handler).handle_request()\n\"\n```\n\n## Step 4: Authorize in the Browser\n\n1. Open the authorization URL from Step 2 in your browser\n2. Notion will ask you to grant access — select the pages/workspace you want\n3. Click **\"Allow access\"**\n4. You'll be redirected to localhost, and the Python script will print the **authorization code**\n\n## Step 5: Exchange the Code for a Token\n\n```bash\ncurl -s -X POST https://api.notion.com/v1/oauth/token \\\n  -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n  -u \"YOUR_CLIENT_ID:YOUR_CLIENT_SECRET\" \\\n  -d '{\n    \"grant_type\": \"authorization_code\",\n    \"code\": \"THE_CODE_FROM_STEP_4\",\n    \"redirect_uri\": \"http://localhost:3333/callback\"\n  }' | python3 -m json.tool\n```\n\nThe response will contain an `access_token`.\n\n## Step 6: Configure LibreFang\n\nIn your `config.toml`:\n\n```toml\n[[mcp_servers]]\nname = \"notion\"\ntimeout_secs = 30\nheaders = [\"Authorization: Bearer ntn_YOUR_ACCESS_TOKEN_HERE\"]\n\n[mcp_servers.transport]\ntype = \"http\"\nurl = \"https://mcp.notion.com/mcp\"\n```\n\n## Notes\n\n- Notion tokens **don't expire** (no refresh token flow) — the token stays valid until the integration is revoked\n- The token only has access to pages explicitly shared with the integration — in Notion, go to a page, click \"...\" > \"Connections\" > add your integration\n- If you created an **Internal** integration instead of Public, you get a simpler \"Internal Integration Secret\" directly on the integration page (no OAuth dance needed), but it's workspace-scoped only",
